<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-07-07T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-07-07T15:00:00-05:00" n="275" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d275">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">123W451/110: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Welles</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-07-07T16:00:00-04:00">July 7, 1933—4
                                    p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>54. Personal for the Ambassador. Could you give me any idea how much
                                longer you feel that, in justice to the work which you are now
                                doing, you should remain in Habana? I realize, of course, that there
                                is still much to be done in the political field, as well as in the
                                negotiations for the revision of the commercial treaty. With me it
                                is a question of considering whether it would be worth while to
                                appoint Caffery Assistant Secretary of State pending your
                                return.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>